":"van 10 januari 1463 to 9 januari 1464","about 1453":"circa 1453","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Donington, Shropshire, England":"Donington, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1463–":"from 10 January 1463 to 9 January 1464–Deceased","1463–Male":"from10January1463to9January1464–Deceased","1455–1521":"1455–1521","1457–Female":"1457–Deceased","1483–1515":"1483–1515","1433–1475":"1433–1475","1483":"1483","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","Abt 1482":"about 1482","1457":"1457","1433":"1433","1521":"1521","1455":"1455","1475":"1475","1463":"from 10 January 1463 to 9 January 1464","about 1453":"about 1453","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Donington, Shropshire, England":"Donington, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spellman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the early Middle English personal name <i>Spileman</i>, <i>Speleman</i>, late Old English <i>Spilemann</i>. Its original sense was probably ‘entertainer’ (literally ‘play-man’), corresponding to Middle High German <i>spilmann</i>, Middle Low German <i>speelman</i> (see above). However, although <i>spile</i> ‘play, sport, revelry’ and <i>spilen</i> ‘to play’ occur in Middle English, there is no evidence for a word <i>spileman</i>, and all the English evidence points to this surname being from the personal name rather than an occupational name.","Irish: in Connacht, an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Spealáin</b> and <b>Ó Spealáin</b> (see   Spillane  ).","Americanized form of German <b>Spellmann</b>: occupational name for a musician or minstrel, from Middle Low German <i>spel</i> ‘play’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."],"variants":[{"name":"Spillane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Ciaran, Donal.","Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Spealáin</b> or <b>Ó Spealáin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Spealán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>speal</i> ‘scythe’. Compare   Smullen  ."]},{"name":"Spillman","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Spellman  .","Americanized form of German <b>Spillmann</b>: variant of   Spielmann  ."]},{"name":"Spelman","meanings":["English and Irish (Galway): variant of   Spellman   and   Spillman  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":85,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":9